{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WJorfBakFwiCGSbNWndL1P","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: The review input is scoped to the lines that changed, not the full content of each modified file.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about parsing/filtering logic — does the diff parsing correctly scope to changed lines only? This is a single module's logic (diff parsing/filtering). It's a function/algorithm boundary.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, or subprocess needed to test this.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Could mock a diff and test that only changed lines are passed. A real GitHub API call isn't needed.\n\n\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM needed — this is about what gets fed TO the LLM.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\n**Minimum level: Unit** — this is about the diff parsing/scoping logic. You can pass a mock diff and verify only changed lines are extracted.\n\n**Behavior 2: Inline comments are attached to the correct positions in the diff view on the pull request.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This tests the mapping of findings to diff positions. The failure mode is: does the position calculation (diff hunk parsing → line number mapping) work correctly? This involves the module that maps findings to GitHub diff positions. Could be a single module's logic (position calculation algorithm).\n- REAL-\n\nINFRA: Testing the actual GitHub API posting requires real HTTP, but the position calculation itself is purely local logic. If I mock the GitHub API and verify the correct position parameters are being sent, that's an integration test covering the diff parser, position mapper, and API client working together. The core question is whether the line position values computed for GitHub's review comment API are accurate, which boils down to the diff hunk parsing and position mapping algorithm.\n\nUnit testing alone can catch wrong position calculations with sample diffs and expected outputs, but since the requirement is that comments appear at the correct positions on the actual pull request, I need to verify the parameters flowing through the entire system. Integration testing with a mocked GitHub API would catch both calculation errors and parameter passing issues. The real failure mode is the position calculation algorithm itself—that's the critical piece.\n\nFor the defect detection behavior, I'm considering whether mocking the LLM breaks the test. If I mock it to always return a canned response, I lose the ability to verify whether a real LLM can actually identify the bug, so this depends on the actual LLM's capabilities.\n\nFor the summary consistency check, I'm looking at whether findings in the top-level summary match the inline comments that were posted. This is purely about the coordination logic between two modules—I can mock the LLM's findings and verify the summary generation uses exactly those findings, since the consistency check itself is deterministic and doesn't require a real LLM.\n\nThe full end-to-end pipeline is different though. That requires actually running against a real pull request with real GitHub API calls to verify the entire sequence works without manual intervention—reading the diff, posting inline comments, and posting the summary all complete successfully.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the probability distribution for each behavior. For scoping to changed lines, parsing the diff logic in isolation is pretty straightforward, so that's mostly a unit test concern. But for correct diff positions, I need to consider whether the position calculation is just a local algorithm or if it requires wiring multiple modules together—the diff parser, position mapper, and API client all need to work in concert, so that's split between unit and integration testing.\n\nActually, looking at the MOCK-MISS rule more carefully: if a bug only surfaces when modules hand off data to each other, then unit testing alone isn't sufficient. The position attachment behavior specifically requires the end-to-end flow where the diff parser outputs positions and the comment module consumes them, potentially with different indexing schemes. That points more toward integration testing catching the real failure mode. Let me adjust the probabilities to reflect that integration testing is more likely to catch position-related bugs than unit testing alone.\n\nNow moving through the remaining behaviors: Behavior 3 is clearly an agentic issue since it's about identifying a real defect, which requires reasoning beyond code execution. Behavior 4 spans multiple modules handling summary and inline comment consistency, so integration testing is most likely to catch that. Behavior 5 is a full pipeline issue involving the entire workflow from parsing through rendering, making workflow-level testing the most appropriate.\n\nLet me map out test descriptions for each behavior that align with their minimum test levels. For Behavior 1, I need a unit test that validates the diff parser extracts only the added lines with their positions from a raw GitHub patch string. For Behavior 3, I need an agentic test that calls the real LLM to verify it can actually identify a defect. For Behavior 4, I need an integration test that wires together the inline poster and summary generator to check consistency. And for Behavior 5, I need a workflow test that runs the complete pipeline with a real PR and real LLM calls. The final test runs the complete automation against a real GitHub PR to verify that diff retrieval, LLM analysis, inline comments, and summary posting all work together end-to-end, with both comment types appearing on the PR afterward.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9433,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9433},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3644bad9-c202-42d8-90e1-16c1e126f8c2","uuid":"e3bb27be-15ff-4d6d-8b3d-901110e9cadf"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WJorfBakFwiCGSbNWndL1P","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01ASmgEL6bDR1Y1t2aXDmSyi","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Review input is scoped to changed lines only, not full file content","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure mode is purely algorithmic: the diff-parsing function either extracts only `+`/`-` lines (and their hunk positions) or it leaks unchanged context lines or full-file content. This is one function's parsing logic with no I/O, no cross-module handoff required to expose the bug, and no LLM dependency. A mock diff string is sufficient.","test_description":"Feed a synthetic GitHub diff patch string — containing one or more hunks with added lines, removed lines, and unchanged context lines — into the function that extracts the reviewable input. Assert that the returned content includes only the changed lines (additions/deletions) and their hunk-relative positions, and contains none of the unchanged context lines or any line from outside the diff.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Inline comments are attached to the correct diff positions","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The position calculation (counting lines from hunk headers to produce GitHub diff-position integers) is local logic, but the real failure boundary is whether the position value flows correctly from the diff parser through to the API client payload. A bug might live in the handoff — e.g., the parser emits 1-indexed positions but the comment builder treats them as 0-indexed, or the wrong hunk offset accumulates across multiple hunks. That inter-module data handoff makes Unit insufficient; the modules must be wired together. No real HTTP or LLM call is needed — mock the GitHub API endpoint and inspect the posted payload.","test_description":"Wire the diff-parsing module, the findings-to-position mapper, and the GitHub API client together using a stubbed HTTP layer. Provide a multi-hunk diff with known structure and a set of pre-computed findings referencing specific file+line combinations. Assert that the position field in each captured API request matches the expected diff-line offset calculated manually from the hunk headers — covering both single-hunk and multi-hunk cases where offset accumulation could go wrong.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.52,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Agent identifies at least one real defect in a PR containing a known introduced bug","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness of this behavior depends entirely on what the real LLM produces. A mocked LLM always returns a canned response and will trivially pass; the failure mode — the model missing the bug — only manifests with a real model call. Detection quality (recall of a specific defect) varies across runs and model versions. This is the definition of LLM-DEP: running the test 100 times with the real model could yield different outcomes.","test_description":"Construct a diff that introduces a known, deliberate bug (e.g., an off-by-one index error or a missing None check before attribute access). Pass this diff to the agent's analysis step using the real LLM. Assert that at least one returned finding references the file and approximate line range of the introduced bug, or uses a category term that correctly describes the defect class. Run with a fixed seed or temperature=0 where the API supports it to reduce variance, but do not mock the model.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Every finding in the top-level summary has a matching inline comment — no orphaned summary entries","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure mode is a consistency invariant broken at the handoff between two modules: the inline-comment posting module and the summary-generation module must operate on the same finding set. A bug could cause the summary to be generated from an earlier, unfiltered list while posted inline comments come from a filtered one (e.g., after skipping comments that failed to post). That divergence is invisible in either module tested alone; both modules must be wired together with a shared findings list to expose it. No real LLM or network call is needed — inject a fixed, deterministic findings list.","test_description":"Inject a fixed list of N findings (using real model instances, not dicts) into the integrated pipeline that runs the inline-comment poster and the summary-comment generator with a stubbed GitHub API. Capture all API calls. Assert that (a) exactly N inline comment requests were made, one per finding, and (b) the summary comment body references exactly those N finding identifiers — no finding appears in the summary whose corresponding inline comment was not among the captured requests. Include a scenario where one inline post is configured to fail, and assert the summary omits that entry.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Full sequence — diff read, inline comments, summary comment — completes on a real PR without manual intervention","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This behavior explicitly requires multiple agentic steps in sequence (GitHub diff retrieval → real LLM analysis → inline comment posting → summary comment posting) against a real pull request. Each step depends on the previous step's real output. Mocking any of these collapses the test to a lower level; real GitHub API calls are needed to verify auth, rate limits, and API format; a real LLM call is needed for the analysis step; and the sequential dependency across steps makes this Workflow rather than just Agentic.","test_description":"Create or designate a real test GitHub pull request with known content and at least one deliberately introduced defect. Run the full automation end-to-end against that PR with the real LLM and real GitHub credentials. After completion, query the GitHub API to assert that (a) at least one inline review comment exists on the PR at a position within the changed lines, (b) a top-level PR comment exists containing a summary, and (c) the automation process exited cleanly with no unhandled exception or manual prompt. Tear down by deleting the test comments after the assertion.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.14,"Workflow":0.75}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9433,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9433},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3644bad9-c202-42d8-90e1-16c1e126f8c2","uuid":"2ad9e204-8a5f-4ef7-85c0-767ee49a01a3"}
